---
import DocsLayout from '../../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import Callout from '../../../../components/Callout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Deployment" description="Deploy FactFeed's full stack to a staging environment.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Deployment</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">Project 1 deployed a static site — one click, done. FactFeed has a backend, a database, and a worker. Deployment is more complex, but the process is the same: direct Claude, verify the result.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4">Why deployment is harder now</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">A static site is just files. A full-stack app needs:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-8">
    <li>A server that runs Docker (or a platform that handles containers)</li>
    <li>A PostgreSQL database accessible from the backend</li>
    <li>Environment variables for database credentials, API keys, and service URLs</li>
    <li>The frontend served and connected to the backend API</li>
    <li>The worker running and able to reach the external facts API</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Direct the deploy</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-2">This is a ticket like any other. Tell Claude:</p>
  <CodeBlock copy>{`Deploy FactFeed to a staging environment. The frontend, backend, database, and worker all need to be running and connected.`}</CodeBlock>
  <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-2 mb-4">Claude will handle the specifics — Docker in production, environment variable setup, and deployment configuration. Your job is verifying it works.</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Deployment errors are more likely here</strong> than in Project 1. That's expected. The fix is the same: read the error, paste it to Claude, direct the fix. You don't need to understand every line of the error — you need to communicate it clearly.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Environment variables</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Full-stack apps use environment variables for configuration that changes between environments. You'll need to set:</p>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-8">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-bg-muted">
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Variable</th>
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Purpose</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr class="border-b border-border"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm">DATABASE_URL</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">PostgreSQL connection string</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm">FACTS_API_URL</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">External facts API endpoint</td></tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border"><td class="px-4 py-3 font-mono text-sm">CORS_ORIGINS</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Allowed frontend origins</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Verification checklist</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Once deployed, verify everything works on the live staging URL:</p>
  <ul class="text-sm text-text-secondary list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-4">
    <li>Frontend loads at the staging URL</li>
    <li>Click "Next Fact" — does a real fact appear?</li>
    <li>Open DevTools → Network tab — does the request go to the live API (not localhost)?</li>
    <li>Check <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">/api/health</code> on the live backend — does it return <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">{'{"status": "ok"}'}</code>?</li>
    <li>Wait 15 minutes, then check — is the fact count increasing? (worker is running)</li>
    <li>Test on your phone — does the card display correctly?</li>
  </ul>

  <details class="mb-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary>Troubleshooting: "The deploy failed"</summary>
    <div class="p-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">Read the error message. Copy it. Paste to Claude: "The deploy failed with this error: [paste]. Fix it." Full-stack deploy errors are often about environment variables, port conflicts, or database connection issues. Claude has seen them all.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details class="my-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary class="px-6 py-4 bg-bg-muted cursor-pointer font-semibold text-sm">The landscape: containers & cloud platforms</summary>
    <div class="px-6 py-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">Docker is one piece of a much larger infrastructure ecosystem. Here's what else exists and where each fits.</p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Docker</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">What we use. Packages your application and its dependencies into containers that run identically everywhere. The industry standard for application packaging.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Docker Compose</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Runs multiple containers together (frontend, backend, database). What we use for local development. Not designed for production at scale.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Kubernetes (K8s)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Container orchestration at scale. Manages hundreds of containers across multiple servers. Used by large companies. Complex but powerful. We'll survey this in Project 9.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">AWS</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Amazon's cloud platform. EC2 for servers, RDS for databases, S3 for storage, CloudFront for CDN. We'll go deep on AWS from Project 6 onwards.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Google Cloud (GCP)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Google's cloud platform. Cloud Run for containers, Cloud SQL for databases, Cloud Storage. Similar to AWS, different naming.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Microsoft Azure</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Microsoft's cloud platform. Dominant in enterprises that use Microsoft tooling (.NET, Teams, Active Directory).</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Terraform</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Infrastructure as Code. Write configuration files that describe your cloud infrastructure, and Terraform creates it. We'll introduce this in Project 6.</span></p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Railway / Render / Fly.io</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Platform-as-a-Service. Deploy containers without managing servers. Simpler than AWS, less control. Good for small projects and MVPs.</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4">Right now you're deploying a full-stack app to a PaaS provider. From Project 6, you'll provision your own infrastructure on AWS using Terraform. The progression: PaaS (someone else manages the server) → IaaS (you manage the server) → IaC (you define infrastructure in code). Each step adds control and responsibility.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-primary-bg rounded-lg border border-primary/20 text-center">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">Next: client review</h2>
    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Staging is live. Time to show the reviewer and get sign-off.</p>
    <a
      href="/web-dev/projects/2/uat"
      class="inline-block bg-primary hover:bg-primary-dark text-white font-semibold py-3 px-6 rounded-md transition-colors min-h-[44px]"
    >
      UAT (User Acceptance Testing) →
    </a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
